'''Yamaya no Taue Odori''' (山屋の田植踊) is a {{ill|rice-planting dance|ja|田植踊|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/rice-planting dance|qq=}}, a type of folk performance passed down in the Yamaya district of {{ill|Shiwa, Iwate|ja|紫波町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shiwa, Iwate|qq=}}, {{ill|Iwate Prefecture|ja|岩手県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwate Prefecture|qq=}}. It was designated as a {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|qq=}} in 1981 (Shōwa 56)<ref name=":0">『わたしたちの文化財』紫波町教育委員会、1993rd year 。</ref>.
== Overview ==
The origins of this dance are unclear, but it is said to have begun during the time of the {{ill|Ōshū Fujiwara clan|ja|奥州藤原氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōshū Fujiwara clan|qq=}}. According to legend, a man named Magoroku, who came to the region for {{ill|gold panning|ja|砂金|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/gold panning|qq=}}, performed rice-planting dances and passed them on to the locals under the guidance of the Sugawara clan, a powerful family in the area<ref name=":0" />. According to other records, Magoroku hailed from Kyoto's Fushimi and managed the Yamaya Otomeishi Pass Gold Mine, known for his artistic skills<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|和書 |title=紫波町文化財調査報告書1992 紫波町の文化財 |year=1992 |publisher=紫波町教育委員会 |pages= |author= |page=77}}</ref>.
The area surrounding the source of the Tennogawa River in Yamaya is close to the Jogyu Mine and Chofuku Gold Mine. It is believed that gold sand was extracted from these deposits, as supported by cultural asset surveys<ref>{{Cite book|和書 |title=紫波町文化財調査報告書2022 町内金鉱山遺跡詳細分布調査報告書 |year=2023 |publisher=紫波町教育委員会 |pages= |author= |page=5}}</ref>. Related arts in the vicinity, such as the "Toyama Taue Odori" and "Funakubo Sansa Odori," share origins connected to gold mining<ref name=":0" />.
Every year, on the 15th day of {{ill|Koshogatsu|ja|小正月|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Koshogatsu|qq=}}, performers gather at the Tanokamisama shrine of the host household to perform the "Kasa Soroe" ritual, marking the beginning of the year's rice-planting dances. Traditionally, during the winter months until February, performers visited the homes of patrons daily, offering prayers for abundant harvests<ref name=":1" />.
The Taue Odori depicts the agricultural process of rice planting, turning it into a ritualistic performance to invoke bountiful harvests, characteristic of {{ill|yoshuku-geino|ja|予祝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/yoshuku-geino|qq=}}. It features two main styles: outdoor performances known as "Niwa Taue" and indoor performances known as "Zashiki Taue." The Yamaya no Taue Odori is primarily a "Zashiki Taue," focusing on dances led by the Saotome performers, with intermediary dances tying the performances together.
The performance begins with an introductory speech, followed by "Sanbasō," and sequentially portrays the year's rice-planting activities through songs and dances. The event is further enlivened with festive entertainment such as Hayashi dances. As a New Year's celebratory ritual, the Yamaya no Taue Odori is a sophisticated and diverse expression of rice-planting culture.
